crophages","Plasma cells"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMacrophages\u003C/strong\u003E are the predominant immune cell type in human breast milk, comprising approximately 40-50% of total milk leukocytes. These cells are actively phagocytic and provide important immune protection to the infant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Elymphocytes\u003C/strong\u003E are present in breast milk, they only make up about 10% of the total immune cells. \u003Cstrong\u003EEosinophils\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ebasophils\u003C/strong\u003E are rarely found in normal breast milk. \u003Cstrong\u003EPlasma cells\u003C/strong\u003E are not typically present in breast milk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe second most common immune cell type in breast milk is neutrophils, comprising about 40-45% of total leukocytes. Together with macrophages, these cells form an important component of the infant\u0027s passive immunity system, helping to protect against various infections.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Human breast milk contains predominantly macrophages and neutrophils, with lymphocytes making up about 10% of total immune cells.","Immune cells in breast milk provide passive immunity to the infant and help protect against infections."],"references":["Ballard O, Morrow AL. Human milk composition: nutrients and bioactive factors. Pediatr Clin North Am. 2013 Feb;60(1):49-74. doi: 10.1016/j.pcl.2012.10.002. PMID: 23178060; PMCID: PMC3586783","Kim SY, Yi DY. Components of human breast milk: from macronutrient to microbiome and microRNA. Clin Exp Pediatr. 2020 Aug;63(8):301-309. doi: 10.3345/cep.2020.00059. Epub 2020 Mar 23. PMID: 32252145; PMCID: PMC7402982","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014).